              </figure>

              Both <m>\vec v</m> and <m>2\vec v</m> are sketched in <xref ref="fig_vect3">Figure</xref>. Make note that <m>2\vec v</m> does not start at the terminal point of <m>\vec v</m>; rather, its initial point is also the origin.</p></li>

          <li><p>The figure suggests that <m>2\vec v</m> is twice as long as <m>\vec v</m>. We compute their magnitudes to confirm this.
              <md>
                <mrow>\norm{\vec v} \amp = \sqrt{2^2+1^2}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{5}.</mrow>
                <mrow>\norm{2\vec v}\amp =\sqrt{4^2+2^2}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{20}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{4\cdot 5} = 2\sqrt{5}.</mrow>
              </md>
              As we suspected, <m>2\vec v</m> is twice as long as <m>\vec v</m>.</p></li>
        </ol>
      </solution>
